[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is the following principle stated anywhere? Or am I confused?</p>\n<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U :  B \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> be a functor between cocomplete categories. An object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a\\in A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is called <em><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>-adjointable</em>, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>hom</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hom(a,U-)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">hom</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is representable. Then the class of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>-adjointable objects is closed under colimits in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. In particular, to prove that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> has a left adjoint, it is sufficient to exhibit \"free\" objects for a class of objects which generate <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> under colimits. </p>\n<p>Proof: If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span></span></span></span> is the colimit of a diagram <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>-adjointable objects, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>hom</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hom(a,U-)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">hom</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is represented by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{colim}(FD)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">colim</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is the partial left adjoint on the category of adjointable objects.</p>\n<p>(I'm asking since Johnstone uses something like this to show that the \"symmetric monad\" exists, and I was wondering why he didn't have to prove well-definedness. But it seems to be a general thing?)</p>",
        "id": 536931342,
        "sender_full_name": "Jonas Frey",
        "timestamp": 1756577495
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just for completeness, let me give Johnstone's argument: we want to show that the  forgetful 2-functor</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U:\\mathsf{Logos}\\to\\mathsf{Pres}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Logos</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Pres</span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>has a left biadjoint, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Logos}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Logos</span></span></span></span></span> is the 2-category of Grothendieck toposes and lex cocontinuous functors, ie inverse image parts of geometric morphisms, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Pres}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Pres</span></span></span></span></span> is the 2-category of locally presentable categories and cocontinuous functors. It is easy to see that free logoses over presheaf categories <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> (viewed as objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Pres}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Pres</span></span></span></span></span>) exist: the free logos on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">x</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(\\mathsf{Lex}(C))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Lex</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> -- the category of presheaves on the free finite-limit category on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>. The existence of the left biadjoint now follows from the above principle since every presentable category is presentable as a coinverter of a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>-cell between cocontinuous functors between presheaf categories.</p>",
        "id": 536933089,
        "sender_full_name": "Jonas Frey",
        "timestamp": 1756579578
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually the left adjoint to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">s</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U:\\mathsf{Logos}\\to\\mathsf{Pres}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Logos</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Pres</span></span></span></span></span> is closely related to (almost and instance of) the use of the adjoint lifting theorem discussed <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/distributive.20laws.20and.20monadic.20functors\">here</a> in the context of distributive laws a while ago. So the above principle seems to be a good way to think about the extension of left adjoints from Kleisli categories to categories of algebras in general.</p>",
        "id": 536933215,
        "sender_full_name": "Jonas Frey",
        "timestamp": 1756579752
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Seems like valid reasoning to me. I've never observed that principle before.</p>",
        "id": 536933329,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1756579883
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Makes sense to me, and I don't remember seeing it written down abstractly anywhere.</p>",
        "id": 536933478,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1756580043
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I believe this is an instance of the following result (which appears in <a href=\"https://arkor.co/files/Monadic%20and%20Higher-Order%20Structure.pdf#page=75\">my thesis</a>), which gives necessary and sufficient conditions for a relative adjunction to extend to an adjunction. (Note that, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is small, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is cocomplete, then the pointwise left extension is guaranteed to exist.)<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/q_WSL-HPDbQPccFlNsVi4d5j/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/q_WSL-HPDbQPccFlNsVi4d5j/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1506x298\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/q_WSL-HPDbQPccFlNsVi4d5j/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>This holds in any proarrow equipment (and more generally any <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/virtual%20equipment\">[[virtual equipment]]</a>), so in particular holds for 2-functors between 2-categories. The same argument works mutatis mutandis to extend relative pseudoadjunctions to pseudoadjunctions.</p>",
        "id": 536962047,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1756620660
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/construction.20of.20left.20adjoint.20by.20generators.20and.20symm.2E.20topos/near/536962047\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The same argument works mutatis mutandis to extend relative pseudoadjunctions to pseudoadjunctions.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>How do you feel about this statement of yours and our policy in citing these kind of results? Should Jonas just say that the theorem follow from a pseudo-version of Prop 5.4.7 in Arkor? Or this is not acceptable. </p>\n<p>My personal answer is that this is a very valid argument, but I can see many referees rejecting a paper based on such justification (this actually happened to me several times).</p>",
        "id": 536973265,
        "sender_full_name": "Ivan Di Liberti",
        "timestamp": 1756636083
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Most importantly, if we think that this is not a valid argument, are we envisaging -- almost suggesting -- that there should be a Pseudo-Arkor, writing a pseudo-version of his PhD thesis to fill the gap in the literature?</p>",
        "id": 536973372,
        "sender_full_name": "Ivan Di Liberti",
        "timestamp": 1756636201
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Maybe I should make my question even more clear: would you, as a referee, be fine with such justification? And if not, what should the author say?)</p>",
        "id": 536973514,
        "sender_full_name": "Ivan Di Liberti",
        "timestamp": 1756636331
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In this specific instance, the proof in the bicategorical case really does just proceed by replacing isomorphisms with equivalences everywhere (and it is clear this works, because the proof is given simply by constructing a chain of isomorphisms). So I don't think I would have a problem with authors simply pointing to the one-dimensional argument. On the other hand, I do not find it reasonable for authors simply to refer to a one-dimensional argument that involves equational reasoning (and hence requires dealing with coherence in two dimensions), because these do not extend from one dimension so evidently.</p>",
        "id": 536975033,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1756638117
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But one can always mollify a reluctant reviewer by including an explicit proof, which is not very long anyway.</p>",
        "id": 536975073,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1756638178
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The famous <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mollifier\">mollifiers</a> for referees....</p>",
        "id": 536987810,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1756651663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/construction.20of.20left.20adjoint.20by.20generators.20and.20symm.2E.20topos/near/536975033\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In this specific instance, the proof in the bicategorical case really does just proceed by replacing isomorphisms with equivalences everywhere (and it is clear this works, because the proof is given simply by constructing a chain of isomorphisms).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>One way to make that more precise is to say that the proof evidently works in a context for formal category theory, like a proarrow equipment, and thus can be specialized directly to the proarrow equipment of bicategories as well (and also to other contexts like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-categories).</p>\n<p>There was a time when I hoped that one day it would become the norm to actually <em>write</em> proofs in a language of formal category theory when possible, saving the reader the trouble of observing that they can be generalized that way.</p>",
        "id": 536994528,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1756659444
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There was a time when I hoped that one day... - the distant past of the far future, the tense used by old mathematicians.   Heck, you might as well <em>still</em> hope that one day it will be the norm.</p>",
        "id": 536996766,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1756661936
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/construction.20of.20left.20adjoint.20by.20generators.20and.20symm.2E.20topos/near/536994528\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>One way to make that more precise is to say that the proof evidently works in a context for formal category theory, like a proarrow equipment, and thus can be specialized directly to the proarrow equipment of bicategories as well (and also to other contexts like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-categories).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The proof in my thesis is in the context of a proarrow equipment. But to establish the result for pseudoadjunctions rather than adjunctions, one would need to reason about equivalences of 1-cells, rather than isomorphisms of 1-cells, and it's not clear to me that this is possible without working with a three-dimensional notion of proarrow equipment?</p>",
        "id": 536997918,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1756663094
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/construction.20of.20left.20adjoint.20by.20generators.20and.20symm.2E.20topos/near/536994528\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There was a time when I hoped that one day it would become the norm to actually <em>write</em> proofs in a language of formal category theory when possible, saving the reader the trouble of observing that they can be generalized that way.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I still have hope :) One thing that I think would help a lot is having an introductory textbook on formal category theory...</p>",
